Given that \(\Gamma \cup \{ 
eg (A \wedge B) \}\) is consistent, there exists a model in which \(\Gamma\) holds and \(
eg (A \wedge B)\) is true; that is, \(
eg A \vee 
eg B\) holds in that model. Therefore, in that model at least one of \(
eg A\) or \(
eg B\) is true. This implies that at least one of the theories \(\Gamma \cup \{
eg A\}\) or \(\Gamma \cup \{
eg B\}\) is consistent. This lends support to statement (2).

Because it is possible for \(\Gamma\) to be such that both \(\Gamma \cup \{
eg A\}\) and \(\Gamma \cup \{
eg B\}\) are consistent (for example, when \(\Gamma\) forces both \(A\) and \(B\) to be false), both \(\Gamma \cup \{ 
eg (A \wedge B) \}\) and \(\Gamma \cup \{ 
eg (A \vee B) \}\) can be consistent in that case. Therefore, statement (1), which claims that at most one of these theories is consistent, is false.

